node.title: Steady advection problem
node.bodyText:
Hi!
I am trying to solve a simple 1D problem comprising of advection and source term:
\partial{phi}/\partial{x}=10
I am expecting results as a straight line phi = 10x
But my input file doesn't converges. Please have a look at my input file. I am using navierstokes module.
Thanks
`[Mesh]
type = GeneratedMesh
dim = 1
xmin = 0
xmax = 10.0
nx = 100
[]
[Variables]
[./phi]
[../]
[]
[Kernels]
[./advection]
type = MassConvectiveFlux
variable = phi
vel_x = 1
[../]
[./rhs]
type = CoupledForce
variable = phi
v = 10
[../]
[]
[BCs]
[./left]
type = DirichletBC
variable = phi
boundary = 'left'
value = 0
[../]
[]
[Executioner]
type = Steady
[]
[Outputs]
exodus = true
[]
`

This is a purely advection equation. You probably need some sort of stabilization, e.g., SUPG.
There are several similar implementation of advection equations and SUPG stabilization in different physics modules. Navier Stokes modules have those implemented, but not for this simple equation. Instead, I used level set module to solve your problem. If you do not add SUPG, the solver will fail due to FACTOR_NUMERIC_ZEROPIVOT. Adding the SUPG term will make it solve.
[Mesh]
  type = GeneratedMesh
  dim = 1
  xmin = 0
  xmax = 10.0
  nx = 10
[]

[Variables]
  [phi]
  []
[]

[AuxVariables]
  [velocity]
    family = LAGRANGE_VEC
  []
[]

[AuxKernels]
  [vec]
    type = VectorFunctionAux
    variable = velocity
    function = velocity_func
    execute_on = 'INITIAL TIMESTEP_END'
  []
[]

[Functions]
  [velocity_func]
    type = ParsedVectorFunction
    expression_x = '1'
  []
[]

[Kernels]
  [advection]
    type = LevelSetAdvection
    velocity = velocity
    variable = phi
  []

  [advection_supg]
    type = LevelSetAdvectionSUPG
    velocity = velocity
    variable = phi
  []

  [rhs]
    type = BodyForce
    variable = phi
    value = 10
  []
[]

[BCs]
  [left]
    type = DirichletBC
    variable = phi
    boundary = 'left'
    value = 0
  []
[]

[Executioner]
  type = Steady
[]
[Outputs]
  exodus = true
[]

Thanks. I tried to run the input file. But "FACTOR_NUMERIC_ZEROPIVOT" is still there.
I have a time dependent PDE in which these terms are present. I am doing this to verify whether each terms are giving the required output. Is there any other way to test individual terms ?
Thanks again!
`*** Warning ***
/Users/prakharverma/projects/newmanmodel/problem/levelset00.i:32: unused parameter 'Functions/velocity_func/expression_x'
0 Nonlinear |R| = 3.041381e+00
0 Linear |R| = 3.041381e+00
Linear solve did not converge due to DIVERGED_PC_FAILED iterations 0
PC failed due to FACTOR_NUMERIC_ZEROPIVOT
Nonlinear solve did not converge due to DIVERGED_LOCAL_MIN iterations 0
Solve Did NOT Converge!
Aborting as solve did not converge`

This unused param makes me think you are using an old version of MOOSE where the parameter had a different name
Please update
Guillaume

Thanks. Updated to latest version. Its working fine now.
However, my other question was:
I have a PDE in which these terms are present. I am doing this to verify whether each terms individually are giving the required output. Is there any other way to test individual terms ?

node.bodyText:
Hello,
Sorry I get confused. To install a app with custom kernels, I have to rebuild MOOSE again?
I installed with HPC instructions. So my steps will be the following. Please correct me if I am wrong.
git clone --recursive https://github.com/idaholab/moose.git

module load StdEnv/2020 gcc boost petsc

cd moose
git checkout master

./configure
./scripts/update_and_rebuild_libmesh.sh --disable-xdr-required

cd test/
make -j 64
./run_tests -j 64

Then building my app -
 cd projects
 ./moose/scripts/stork.sh dendrite

 cd dendrite
added  custom .h files in dendrite/include/kernels and custom.c files in dendrite/src/kernels
 vim Makefile
PHASE_FIELD                 := yes
TENSOR_MECHANICS            := yes
 make -j 4

You need to install moose again every time you modify the kernels
hwowever the build system should be smart enough to only recompile what has changed

An InterfaceKernel is much like an IntegratedBC.
It might make things easier to think about the physics that CoupledPenaltyInterfaceDiffusion suggests, so let's imagine having just diffusion on either side of the interface. When you integrate a diffusion problem by parts, you wind up with the surface term <test, -normals * grad u>. Now imagine we have integrated by parts on the other side: <test_neighbor, normals * grad v>
Now by writing the element residual: <test, penalty * (u - v)>, what you have implicitly done is set: -normals * grad u = penalty * (u - v)
And similarly if you set the neighbor residual: <test_neighbor, -penalty * (u - v)>, then you have implicitly set: normals * grad v = -penalty * (u - v)
So what have you done? Looking at those two implicit equations you can see you've set: -normals * grad u = -normals * grad v = penalty * (u - v)
So by the first equality you have set continuity of flux (diffusive flux). And through the penalty parameter you are driving u and v to be equal to each other.
Generalizing this to the FSI problem, you are asking for continuity of stress between the fluid and solid, and you are driving the difference in velocities (liquid and solid) to zero. So stress for the fluid in this case (where you are using the Laplace form for the viscous term and have integrated the pressure by parts), when dotted with the normal, is component-wise: <test, p * normals(component) - mu * grad v_component * normals> where v is the velocity, and v_component is a component of the velocity. So this fluid stress will be made equal to whatever stresses exist in the solid phase.

derivatives() is a MetaPhysicL routine for retrieving derivatives of a dual number in forward mode automatic differentiation.
For the common AD use case where you are interested in the derivative of a function g(f) with a known variable f and its known derivatives df/dx, forward mode AD gives you the dual number (g, dg/dx) by evaluating g(f).
The code snippet you showed above is a more advanced usage of MetaPhysicL's forward AD. For the more advanced use case, we are using forward mode AD to also compute the second derivative.
The comment in the source file does a good job at explaining what's happening:
  /**
   * computeThermalStrain must be overridden in derived classes. The return type
   * ValueAndDerivative<is_ad> contains the value for the thermal strain and its
   * temperature derivative. Derived classes should use `_temperature[_qp]` to obtain
   * the current temperature. In the is_ad == false case that member variable is
   * agumented and will be of the type ChainedReal. I.e. even with is_ad == false
   * a variant of forward mode automatic differentiation will be used internally to
   * compute the thermal strain and no manual implementation of the temperature derivative
   * is needed.
   */
